Updated: i initially rated this at 3 because the zoom-fast movement makes it impossible to navigate effectively while moving around. The developer quickly responded and pointed out that it's possible to force no-run mode by dragging the right on-screen button to the right and holding it there (it will change into a "feet" icon). With that movement problem resolved i can, in good conscience, rate this as a 5. The novel controls make great use of the touchscreen, there's tons of content, many options for character customization, good writing with plenty of geeky references, and active support/responses from the developers.
replyContent: Hello Stephan, thank you for the review, we will consider an option to toggle the cursor sensitivity, or the "walk/run mode" in the game options in a future update.

A fantastic adventure riddled with old school gaming and fantasy references. It's a bit heavy handed but fun and light hearted regardless. Combat is turned based. There's a wealth of items, abilities, and options for customizing the fighting style of your party members. Often challenging, the game forces you to plan and think about the directions you want to take your characters and each battle. Plenty of additional dialogue and secrets for you to discover in handmade maps that will snack you right in the nostalgia center of your brain. All around a solid classic style RPG that I can confidently give a 10/10.

Nicely done. A fully made rpg/jrpg that pokes fun and plays off of rpg 
tropes. There's a lot of clever writing. There are nice little notes on the 
wall here and there. The controls are actually pretty well done on mobile. 
While the writing is made to spoof and joke about RPGs, this an actual game 
in its own right. This game makes me feel like I'm playing an old (SNES 
era?) rpg, with its own battle mechanics and conditions. It's kept my 
interest and attention, and I'm looking forward to seeing how it plays out. 
Definitely recommend giving it a try.

I feel that most game apps are severely lacking or just greedy. But every once in awhile, I find one that is worthwhile. One that I feel is worth making that one payment, not to remove the ads or have a full game, but to support the creators.  Even with that I still rarely take the time to comment.   Good job guys, I look forward to playing your sequel/revamp/ prequel. This game has both intrigued and amused me. For the life of me I can't figure out why these RPGs so often release a game like this without some kind of reasonable auto battle capability. It would be very easy to implement a rudimentary conditions engine to allow you to select the commands you use routinely. At the bare minimum it should remember your last command so that you can hit a turbo button, or like in this game hold a button, to automatically execute the last command. This game only allows you to repeat the Attack command, which is close to useless when you have two of four magic using characters. What is this, 1987? The constant touch touch slide touch just to execute magic/skill commands ruins what otherwise was a fun game. Uninstalled.

Updated: fixed.                 How do I turn game off?  The game was great on Xbox.
replyContent: You simply press the home button, the operative system will close the game when it need more memory. If you wish to close the game at all costs simply open the task manager from the home screen and swipe it away to close it forcibly. On Android you shouldn't need to close the app (and no programming way to do it aside willingly crashing the app).

I actually got this game as an Amazon free app of the day the other day but it is so good I am actually buying it on the Google Play store just to throw the developers some cash.  I have spent over 7 hours in it so far, which is unheard of in a mobile game for me.  The humor is great and pokes fun/references a huge swath of nerd culture.  Beyond that, the gameplay is fantastic.  There are random battles, but they aren't too frequent.  The actual battles also strike a great balance in difficulty so you they aren't super hard but aren't trivial either.  Maps/dungeons are likewise balanced, they never lose sight of the fact that it is a mobile game.  While they have updated the old school aesthetic and gameplay to remove the really annoying parts, it is still closer to a snes jrpg than it is to an elder scrolls game.  Just a heads up to those of you too young to remember life before HD ;)

My ONLY complaint is that there aren't more games like this from the devs. Keep them coming guys, and I'll keep buying them!

I keep getting a sound bug after a battle finishes and it counts the gold earned. The gold ticking sound gets constantly repeated and I can't stop it unless I force close the app or restart the phone. Please look into this issue.     Also in regards to a reply you have made recently to another review: it is not true that the only way to close an app is to hit home and go to recent apps. Android apps by default will close fully from pressing back in the main screen. You have somehow blocked this action.
replyContent:
Thanks for reporting the sound issue, can you please tell us if this happens every time you finish a battle?
As for the back button issue, i have tested the back button on most devices and all it does is actually sending leaving the app in background and resetting it.

content: Had played about 40 minutes so far, through the first chapter, but they were stellar! The two things that stand out the most about the game, for me, are the intuitive two-stick controls and the common sense writing - the second spell Nigel gets really had me laughing and enjoying the writing. I do have one issue, although it doesn't directly detract from the fun: at the main menu I can't press back (at least on Jellybean, using an Asus Trasnformer Prime) to exit the game. I must click the home button and then open recent programs and close the app. Fixing this would be a convience, although the game gets 5 stars from me anyway.
replyContent:
we noticed that on android the "shut down" botton doesn't work, 'cause the only way to shut down an app is via home button and close the recent program :P if we became better programmer we will try to solve this issue :D
anywhay thanks for the support!

About 11 hours in... I haven't noticed any graphic problems others have reported (after update some between scenes). Controls are fine, better than most touch-screen controls. Story is great, not too serious, funny and full of pop references. The variety of weapons and monsters are a bit limited, but all in all one the best jrpgs on the android OS, and one of only a small handful I'll see to the end. Edit: actually the variety of weapons and monsters picks up later on, so yeah great game.

Doom and Destiny hit all the right nostalgia buttons from the start, both for tabletop gaming and classic jrpgs. More than that though, is the fact that it's just a darn fun game! I was pleasently surprised when I realized I was enjoying the game all on its own :)
So awesome to have a real RPG that is Not just another FF clone! Touch screen controls are so simple it threw me at first but become very intuitive.

Fixed some stability issues, it still freezes my phone or crashes occasionally, but at least now it's playable, and from what I've experienced, it's humorous, interesting, and well worth checking out, if you're an rpg fan, its a must have.
